SIMPLE: menial
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Menial
<hw>Men"ial</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>meneal</ets>, fr. <ets>meine</ets>, <ets>maine</ets>, household,
OF. <ets>maisni⟦eacute⟧e</ets>, <ets>maisnie</ets>, LL.
<ets>mansionaticum</ets>. See <er>Mansion</er>, and cf. <er>Meine</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>, <er>Meiny</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Belonging to a retinue or train of servants;
performing servile office; serving.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Two <qex>menial</qex> dogs before their master pressed.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Pertaining to servants, esp. domestic servants;
servile; low; mean; <as>as, <ex>menial</ex> tasks</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧
<xex>Menial</xex> offices.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Swift.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Menial</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Menial
<hw>Men"ial</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A domestic servant or
retainer, esp. one of humble rank; one employed in low or servile
offices.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A person of a servile character or
disposition.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meniere's disease</ent>⟦br⟧
